00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:25.310
&gt;&gt; Catalina Gómez: We are
delighted to start this new series.

00:00:25.310 --> 00:00:30.580
We're starting a series called Poet
2 Poet, Poeta a Poeta, and we --

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:37.870
our idea is to have a poet, a poet
who's alive, to honor one of the --

00:00:37.870 --> 00:00:40.830
a great poet of the
Hispanic language.

00:00:40.830 --> 00:00:45.180
We are starting this great
series here today with Consuelo,

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:47.990
who's going to be doing a
homage to César Vallejo.

00:00:47.990 --> 00:00:51.410
I want to take an opportunity
to also tell you

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:54.970
about the Hispanic Reading Room
of the Library of Congress.

00:00:54.970 --> 00:00:57.780
The Hispanic Reading Room
is a primary access point

00:00:57.780 --> 00:01:01.300
for research related to the
Caribbean, Latin America, Spain,

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:03.750
and Portugal and is
open to everyone.

00:01:03.750 --> 00:01:06.270
Whoever has a reader's card
can use our Reading Room

00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:07.840
so everyone is welcome.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:11.200
If anyone wants to find out
more about our programs,

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:20.170
please visit our website, which
is www.loc.gov/rr/hispanic.

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:22.920
And now to today's event.

00:01:22.920 --> 00:01:25.910
We're going to have Consuelo, who's
going to do a homage to, as I said,

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:27.970
Peruvian poet César Vallejo,

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:32.190
one of our most beloved
poets of Latin America.

00:01:32.190 --> 00:01:37.780
And then Consuelo's going to
read from Vallejo together

00:01:37.780 --> 00:01:42.800
with Maureen Contreni, who is
going to read the poems in English,

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:45.660
and then Consuelo is
going to move --

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:50.160
she's going to then read some of
her work and Contreni is going

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.690
to read the English translations.

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:56.640 position:56%
About our feature speakers, Consuelo
Hernández was born in Colombia

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:01.860
and has lived in Venezuela, Peru,
Puerto Rico, and the United States.

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:04.680
She has published four
collections of poems,

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:08.560
among them Voces de la
soledad, Solo de violín,

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:12.990
poemario para músicos y
pintores, Manual de peregrina,

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:18.250
and the bilingual collection
Poemas de escombros y cenizas,

00:02:18.250 --> 00:02:22.150
and in English that one is titled
Poems from Debris and Ashes,

00:02:22.150 --> 00:02:23.900
and the book that we're here to --

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:25.870
to celebrate, and the one
that she'll be reading

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:29.220
from today, Mi reino sin orillas.

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:32.210
Consuelo's poetry has been
included in numerous anthologies.

00:02:32.210 --> 00:02:35.870
She has received many, many
honors, including distinction

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:41.030
from the international poetry
contest of Ciudad Melilla in Spain

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:45.170
and the Letras de Oro contest
at the University of Miami.

00:02:45.170 --> 00:02:50.860 position:56%
She is also -- in 2011, she received
the Antonio Machado Poetry Award

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.570
in Madrid, Spain, and
the Mid-Atlantic Council

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:57.170
of Latin American Studies,
among many other honors.

00:02:57.170 --> 00:03:01.650
And Consuelo is also Associate
Professor at the World Languages

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:05.620
and Cultures Department at American
University here in Washington.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:09.600
As I said, she will be
accompanied by Maureen Contreni,

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:15.740
who has translated some of
Consuelo's poetry, and Maureen --

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:19.470
Maureen graduated also
from American University.

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.430
That's where she met Consuelo.

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:25.930
And she's an attorney, and she has
traveled extensively throughout

00:03:25.930 --> 00:03:28.980
Latin America, so I'm assuming
that's why you love translating

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:30.680
Latin American poetry.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:33.770
One last announcement.

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:38.300
We will be selling -- Consuelo
is selling her book at the book

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:43.050
and maybe she'll be glad to
sign some copies at the end.

00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:47.950
So the books are located
there in the back.

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:52.590
With no further adieu, please join
me in welcoming Consuelo Hernández.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:54.390
Thank you.

00:03:54.390 --> 00:04:01.790
[ Applause ]

