00:06:02.180 --> 00:06:05.980
the worst catastrophe,
natural catastrophe,

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:09.400
that they have suffered
in the last decades.

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:14.550
And Trujillo, the city
where Vallejo spent most

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:20.810
of his more important
intellectual and formational years,

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:23.570
is one of the cities more affected.

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:29.360
So we have that day in mind today.

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:35.500
It is a great pleasure for
me and a big honor to be

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:42.110
in this city celebrating the
greatest, the most wonderful,

00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:47.810
and the most beloved poet or Latin
American during the 20th century.

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:52.840
César Vallejo is the poet --

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:57.580
is the poet really from
the avant-garde times.

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:05.730
He was a poet that before Breton
published the Surrealist Manifesto

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:11.660
he was already surrealist
[inaudible] he lives only 46 years,

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:23.500
from 1892 to 1918, but
those years were enough

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:30.410
to write an immortal --
immortal book of poetry.

00:07:30.410 --> 00:07:37.410
At the beginning of the year, I was
contacted by Catalina and asked me

00:07:37.410 --> 00:07:42.630
to give the name of one poet that
has been influencing my world

00:07:42.630 --> 00:07:44.650
or somebody that I really like

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:49.820
and honestly I couldn't
give her only one name.

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:54.670
There are many poets that I
have read and many that I enjoy,

00:07:54.670 --> 00:08:00.200
so I sent a list of
six names and let her

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:06.110
to choose whoever she consider more
appropriate to start the series.

00:08:06.110 --> 00:08:12.230
And some days later, I
received a letter, an email,

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:15.620
telling me that the selected
poem was César Vallejo

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:24.180
and I was just thrilled and in some
way I thought what a coincidence

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:28.420
because Vallejo is one of those
very few poets that when I read

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:31.350
for the first time
he moved me to tears.

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:36.870
And I think that everybody
who reads Vallejo can cry

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:39.020
when you read those poems.

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:44.540
So I -- I start to think what
do I have in common with Vallejo

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:48.750
and I really don't know how
much of Vallejo's in my poetry.

00:08:48.750 --> 00:08:52.060
I'm going to leave this
word for the critics,

00:08:52.060 --> 00:08:56.510
but I try to find some comparalisms
[phonetic] between his life

00:08:56.510 --> 00:09:01.170
and my life and the motivation
he has to write poetry

00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:03.220
and my own motivations and I --

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:07.830
I'm going just to mention some
because I think it is useful

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:10.350
to illustrate who was this Vallejo.

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:19.120
One thing in common is
that we're born on March 16

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:23.030
and March 16 is his
date when he's born

00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:28.170
and March 16 is my
official birthday.

00:09:28.170 --> 00:09:31.780
Another thing is our
provincial origins.

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:39.290
He was born in Santiago de
Chuco in Peru highlands,

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:46.640
in a provincial town, in an
environment very religious.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:53.950
His parents were both mestizo
and they were son and daughter

00:09:53.950 --> 00:10:05.080
from priests in Peru so they
have that religious formation

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:09.280
since the very beginning.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:15.220
So I thought that that was
interesting because I'm also

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:19.550
from a little town in Colombia,
from the Andean mountains,

00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:27.560
one hour from Medellín, El Peñón,
and I lived there for 10 years.

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:33.600 position:56%
Vallejo moved from Santiago de Chuco
to Trujillo and to Lima in order

00:10:33.600 --> 00:10:37.630
to study and I moved
when I was 10 to --

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:42.690
with my family to Medellín
also to get education

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:44.860
and go to the university.

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:47.340
By the way, here is
one of my professors

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:50.520
from the University of Antioquia.

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:55.400
I was really surprised because he
was my professor I think 50 years

00:10:55.400 --> 00:11:03.570
ago, around that, and she's also a
translator, Patricia [Inaudible].

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:15.660
And then Vallejo, after those years
in Trujillo and in Lima started

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:21.520
in an agrarian intellectual
development, he decided to go

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:27.750
to France, and from France
he travelled to the Institute

00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:31.220
of [Inaudible], especially
to Russia.

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:35.260
He went four times because
of his political convictions.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:39.100
And then he went also
to Spain to collaborate

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:41.600
with the republican courts.

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:46.380
In my case, I moved to
Venezuela more by spiritual

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:51.810
and idealistic convictions,
too, and [inaudible] political

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:59.300
and then I went to Peru, to
Puerto Rico, and finally I came

00:11:59.300 --> 00:12:02.670
to the United States
where I did my Ph.D.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:12.510
and I definitely stayed
here already 30 years.

00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:19.070
So, but the -- our similarities
in our lives doesn't end here.

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:26.680
We -- I think what delineates his
poetry is also common to my poetry.

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:35.230
He has -- he's chosen his
poetry on profound necessity

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:42.170
and absolutely freedom and at the
same the possibility to find it.

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:46.250
His nostalgia also for his lost
paradise of the [inaudible],

00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:50.980
the memories of his family,
especially his mother

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:55.310
and his brother, his
suffering for the loss --

00:12:55.310 --> 00:12:59.190
losses that he had during his life.

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:09.570
He lost his brother in 1915, his
mother in 1918, then his father.

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:13.570
He was also in jail for 112 days.

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:19.600
So he has a very difficult life
and that shows in his poetry, too.

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:25.460
And he has an existential
anguish and a kind of sense

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:31.520
of feeling an orphan in this
world, lonely, in solitude,

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:40.520
and besides that he had the
conscience for political

00:13:40.520 --> 00:13:46.930
and social justice, and
that put him into trouble

00:13:46.930 --> 00:13:49.530
because of his political
convictions.

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:52.730
He was expelled from France
and he had to live in Spain

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:57.410
for certain times and
he went back to Spain.

00:13:57.410 --> 00:14:04.200
But anyway, in his poetry there are
also the eternal themes of poetry,

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:07.290
death, love, life, and
in a way this is --

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:14.570
this is also present in my poetry,
so I think that the selection

00:14:14.570 --> 00:14:20.110
of César Vallejo was a very
just for our reading today.

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:26.010
But we are not here to hear
another scholarly presentation.

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:30.770
This is something that you can read

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:36.030
in many critic studies
about his poetry.

00:14:36.030 --> 00:14:41.710
There are also many biographies
and some of them exceptional,

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:45.400
like the one written by
Juan Espejo Asturrizaga.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:52.500
So we are going to go into
his poetry and I am going

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:58.100
to try and put into context.

00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:05.070
Any time I read a poem, I am
going to put it into context

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:11.710
and Maureen is going to
read the translation.

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:14.600
He wrote several books of poetry,

00:15:14.600 --> 00:15:19.160
but when he died he
only had published two

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:21.500
and both self-published.

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:27.620
I want to emphasize that
they were self-published

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:34.200
because many times we devaluate
self-publications and one gigantic

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:37.780
like this published Los
heraldos negros [inaudible]

00:15:37.780 --> 00:15:45.230
that doesn't have any translation
because it's a word, a neologismo,

00:15:45.230 --> 00:15:48.480
it's a word invented
by him [inaudible].

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:53.240
He published by himself
with his own money

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:56.210
in Lima before going to France.

00:15:56.210 --> 00:16:04.180 position:56%
And since he went to Europe he
didn't publish any other poetic book

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:08.750
and all the rest of his work
was unpublished until he died.

00:16:08.750 --> 00:16:12.490
His widow was the one that
published the other books.

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:17.270
So this is his complete
work on poetry and half

00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:20.400
of this was unpublished
when he died.

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:24.710
So we're going to start the reading

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:30.000
with one poem entitled
Los heraldos negros.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:39.760 position:56%
Esta poema de Los heraldos negro
abre este libro y habla de el choque

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:47.530
tremendo que tuvo César Vallejo
cuando recibió un telegrama de su

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:52.640
hermano que decía sobre
la muerte de su madre.

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:54.940
Entonces --

00:16:59.110 --> 00:17:04.280
Es un poema muy fuerte y muy bello.

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:06.190
Los heraldos negros.

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:11.830
Hay golpes en la vida, tan fuertes.

00:17:11.830 --> 00:17:14.760
Yo no sé.

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:20.970
Golpes como del odio de
Dios, como si -- si --

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:25.590
Lo siento.

00:17:25.590 --> 00:17:27.510
Necesito [inaudible].

00:17:27.510 --> 00:17:57.460
[ Background speaking ]

00:17:57.460 --> 00:18:00.640
Volvamos a empezar.

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:01.940
Los heraldos negros.

00:18:01.940 --> 00:18:05.220
Hay golpes en la vida, tan fuertes.

00:18:05.220 --> 00:18:08.320
Yo no sé.

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:15.860
Golpes como del odio de
Dios, como si ante ellos,

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:21.170
la resaca de todo lo sufrido
se empozara en el alma.

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:22.470
Yo no sé.

00:18:22.470 --> 00:18:25.100
Son pocos, pero son.

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:33.820
Abren zanjas oscuras en el rostro
más fiero y en el lomo más fuerte.

00:18:33.820 --> 00:18:37.650
Serán tal vez los potros
de bárbaros attilas,

00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:40.960
o los heraldos negros
que nos manda la Muerte.

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:45.130
Son las caídas hondas
de los cristos del alma,

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:51.320
de alguna fe adorable
que el Destino blasfema.

00:18:51.320 --> 00:18:57.750
Esos golpes sangrientos son las
crepitaciones de algún pan que en

00:18:57.750 --> 00:19:00.050
la puerta del horno se nos quema.

00:19:00.050 --> 00:19:02.790
Y el hombre.

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:04.940
Pobre. Pobre.

00:19:04.940 --> 00:19:10.780
Vuelve los ojos, como cuando por
sobre el hombro nos llama una

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:17.930
palmada, vuelve los ojos locos,
y todo lo vivido se empoza,

00:19:17.930 --> 00:19:22.110
como un charco de culpa,
en la mirada.

00:19:22.110 --> 00:19:26.730
Hay golpes en la vida, tan fuertes.

00:19:26.730 --> 00:19:29.030
Yo no sé.

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:37.150
&gt;&gt; Maureen Contreni: Thank you
very much for having me here.

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:40.020
The black heralds.

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:42.920
There are blows in
life, so powerful.

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:44.420
I don't know.

00:19:44.420 --> 00:19:50.040
Blows like God's hatred
as if before them.

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:54.310
the undertow of everything
suffered or to well up in the soul.

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:56.000
I don't know.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.280
They're few, but they exist.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:03.920
They open dark furrows in
the most ferocious face

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:06.510
and the most powerful loins.

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:10.330
Perhaps they're wooden
horses of barbaric attilas

00:20:10.330 --> 00:20:14.490
or black messengers
that Death sent to us.

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:19.030
They're profound lapses
of the soul's christs,

00:20:19.030 --> 00:20:23.340
of some adorable faith
that Destiny blasphemes.

00:20:23.340 --> 00:20:28.140
Those bloodthirsty blows
are crackling of some bread

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:32.300
that in the oven's
door burns up on us.

00:20:32.300 --> 00:20:36.790
And man. Poor, poor man.

00:20:36.790 --> 00:20:42.920
